## Documentation Impact (high-level)

- **`README.md`** — add a top-level capability bullet for MCP, with a one-line example for both directions.
- **`CHANGELOG.md`** — entry for the MCP minor-version release.
- **`README.md`** (already noted above) — capability bullet + one-line example for both directions.
- **`CHANGELOG.md`** (already noted above) — minor-version entry.
- **CLI documentation** — new section covering MCP server configuration in TOML, the Claude-Code import helper, the publish command, and the security / allowlist posture.
- **Library documentation** — new guide for the library-side MCP API, including the multi-server case, error handling, and capability negotiation.
- **API reference** — new entries for any new public types and surfaces introduced.
- **Runnable examples** — new examples covering: consume a public MCP server, expose gadgets as an MCP server, and the round-trip case.
- **Configuration reference** — new TOML schema documented alongside existing config blocks.
- **Security documentation** — disclosure of the stdio allowlist posture, CVE-2026-30623 context, and guidance for users who need to opt in.
- **`CLAUDE.md`** — add MCP-related commands and expectations to the standard task list.

---

## Out of Scope

- OAuth 2.1, dynamic client registration, RFC9728 PRM, RFC8414 ASM, RFC8707 resource indicators (full authorization stack — separate spec).
- MCP "sampling" primitive (server-initiated client LLM calls) — separate spec when demand arrives.
- MCP "elicitation" primitive (mid-call user prompts) — separate spec when demand arrives.
- MCP "roots" primitive — deferred to v1.5 alongside Resources.
- HTTP+SSE legacy transport — explicit deprecation; will not be implemented.
- Hosted, multi-tenant llmist-as-a-remote-MCP-service — out of scope; v1 is local stdio only.
- Bidirectional bridge / proxy mode (translate stdio ↔ HTTP transparently) — third-party tools cover this.
- Replacing native gadgets or the gadget block format with native LLM tool calling — orthogonal to MCP.
- Support for unofficial MCP forks or transport variants (WebSockets, IPC sockets, custom binary).
- A first-party llmist registry of MCP servers — leave registry hosting to glama.ai, mcp.so, the official registry, etc.
- Sandboxing primitives beyond the allowlist (chroot, seccomp, container isolation) — defer to operator setup.
- An MCP server browser / GUI inside the TUI — defer until the surface stabilizes.
